description: From Middle English nyne, nine, from Old English nigon, from Proto-West Germanic *neun, from Proto-Germanic *newun, from Proto-Indo-European *h₁néwn̥.

entries.meaning: (card games) A playing card with nine pips.
(computing, engineering, usually in the plural) A statistical unit of proportion (of reliability, purity, etc.).
examples: They guaranteed that our Web site would have 99.99% uptime, or four nines.

entries.meaning: (baseball) A baseball club, team, or lineup (composed of nine players).
examples: The St. Louis club is the only nine in the league which gives its patrons the right to see a full game or no pay.
